# Chapter 4 — Old Bones (Sitavana / Rajgir, India)

*Keeper-facing summary of Chapter 4 of The Children of Fear. Structure lives in
the sibling `.arc`, stat blocks in the `.actor`, campaign lore in
`children-of-fear-0.4-campaign-overview.lore`. Consult your copy of the campaign
for full text, read-aloud passages, and handouts. One of the three any-order
"Gathering" chapters (see the campaign `FLOW`).*

## Role in the campaign

A Gathering chapter whose component objective is to obtain the **ritual
instruments fashioned from human remains** — the "fife and drum" of tantric
practice — from **Sitavana**, one of the eight great ancient charnel (cremation)
grounds, at **Rajgir** in India (near Bodh Gaya). It is the campaign's darkest
chapter in tone: it deals openly in bones, corpses, and the ethics of taking
them, so the **Dark Materials** content caution applies especially here.

## Getting there

Because it's a middle chapter, arrival varies by the party's route. Coming from
**Derge (Ch5)**, the practical path is via **Chamdo (Qamdo)** and a spur of the
**Tea Horse Road**, then rail ("Glorious Steam" / trains). The lama **Tenzin
Kalsang** may or may not accompany the party depending on earlier choices ("In
Absentia").

## Structure and key beats

**The Jewel in Many Crowns / Holy Ground.** Background on Rajgir and its sacred
charnel ground of Sitavana — the historical and religious weight of the site.

**Set Up — Hot and Cold.** Establishes the objective: the ritual requires
instruments made from specific human remains sourced from this cremation ground.

**Start — Beneath the Trees (Rajgir).** The party arrives at the old city's valley
and its charnel ground; the **Tokabhaya** press on with their imposed visions
(*Visions in the Dark — Sitavana*).

**The Ash-Smeared Sadhu.** A key NPC — a fearsome, ash-covered holy man dwelling at
the charnel ground, feared by locals; a gatekeeper/source for what the party
needs.

**The Bone Collectors / A Dark Harvest.** The grim work of acquiring the required
remains and having the instruments made — with real moral and legal weight (the
chapter flags severe punishment for murder and the risk of drawing suspicion).

**Fife and Drum / Dead Reckoning.** Assembling the actual instrument components;
handling the remains risks Sanity, with body-horror repercussions on failed rolls.

**Optional Encounter — The Scorpion Demon.** A Mythos/demonic set-piece the Keeper
can deploy.

**Moving On — The End of the Road: Sitavana.** With the instruments secured (and
without having enraged local ruffians or the Rajgir authorities), the component is
complete.

## Key NPCs & threats

- **The Ash-Smeared Sadhu** — the charnel-ground holy man; pivotal to the objective.
- **The Bone Collectors** — those who gather/prepare the remains.
- **Tenzin Kalsang** — the Tibetan lama and quest-giver (present or absent per prior choices).
- **The Scorpion Demon** — optional demonic encounter. (Stat blocks in the `.actor`.)
- **British Indian authorities / local ruffians** — mundane complications for a grim errand.

## Clues & handouts (as information)

- Chapter handouts (incl. *Song 3*, referenced here) and the regional *What Your
  Investigator Knows* material for India/Bihar & Orissa.

## Keeper guidance

- Foreground the **Dark Materials** caution: bones, corpses, and murder are on the
  table; check in with players.
- The Ash-Smeared Sadhu is the fulcrum — play the dread he inspires, then the
  transactional path through him.
- Self-contained enough to slot before or after Chapters 3 and 5.

## Transition

Securing the bone instruments checks off a Gathering objective. The party moves to
another middle chapter or, once all three are complete, to the Climax.
